les; <sd-tag id="sdTag100" source="sdapi" category="None" entity_type="gene" role="intervention" text="pif4" ext_ids="818903" ext_dbs="" in_caption="True" ext_names="PIF4" ext_tax_ids="3702" ext_tax_names="Arabidopsis thaliana" ext_urls="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/">pif4</sd-tag>;<sd-tag id="sdTag101" source="sdapi" category="None" entity_type="gene" role="intervention" text="pif5" ext_ids="825075" ext_dbs="" in_caption="True" ext_names="PIL6" ext_tax_ids="3702" ext_tax_names="Arabidopsis thaliana" ext_urls="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/">pif5</sd-tag> 27Â°C data: dashed red lines, open circles).</p> <graphic href="https://api.sourcedata.io/file.php?panel_id=20385"/></sd-panel><sd-panel panel_id="20386"><p><sd-tag id="sdTag103" source="sdapi" category="None" entity_type="protein" role="assayed" text="CO" ext_ids="Q39057" ext_dbs="" in_caption="True" ext_names="CO" ext_tax_ids="3702" ext_tax_names="Arabidopsis thaliana" ext_urls="https://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/">CO</sd-tag> protein data in LDs (16L:8D) in WT at 22 and 27Â°C (as in F).</p> <graphic href="https://api.sourcedata.io/file.php?panel_id=20386"/></sd-panel><sd-panel panel_id="20387"><p><sd-tag id="sdTag165" source="sdapi" category="None" entity_type="gene" role="assayed" text="FT" ext_ids="842859" ext_dbs="" in_caption="True" ext_names="FT" ext_tax_ids="3702" ext_tax_names="Arabidopsis thaliana" ext_urls="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/">FT</sd-tag> mRNA data in LDs in WT and the <sd-tag id="sdTag106" source="sdapi" category="None" entity_type="gene" role="intervention" text="pif4" ext_ids="818903" ext_dbs="" in_caption="True" ext_names="PIF4" ext_tax_ids="3702" ext_tax_names="Arabidopsis thaliana" ext_urls="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/">pif4</sd-tag>;<sd-tag id="sdTag107" source="sdapi" category="None" entity_type="gene" role="intervention" text="pif5" ext_ids="825075" ext_dbs="" in_caption="True" ext_names="PIL6" ext_tax_ids="3702" ext_tax_names="Arabidopsis thaliana" ext_urls="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/">pif5</sd-tag> mutant at 22 and 27Â°C (as in F)</p> <graphic href="https://api.sourcedata.io/file.php?panel_id=20387"/></sd-panel><sd-panel panel_id="20388"><p>FT mRNA simulation in LDs in WT and the pif4;pif5 mutant at 22 and 27Â°C (WT 22Â°C simulation: as in B-E; pif4;pif5 22Â°C simulation: dashed black lines; WT 27Â°C simulation: red lines; pif4;pif5 27Â°C simulation: dashed red lines).</p> <graphic href="https://api.sourcedata.io/file.php?panel_id=20388"/></sd-panel></fig><fig id="6635"><title>Coherent feed-forward networks coordinate the regulation of FT by the circadian clock.</title><label>Figure 7</label><graphic href="https://api.sourcedata.io/file.php?figure_id=6635"/><sd-panel panel_id="20389"><p>Coherent feed-forward networks coordinate the regulation of <sd-pretag id="sdPretag14719624250890" parent-tag-id="150">FT</sd-pretag> by the circadian clock</p><p>As highlighted in the discussion, the flowering system is based on a combination of coherent feed-forward pathways, allowing a single component to play multiple reinforcing roles in the system (Mangan  Alon,2003). This is highlighted here in the case of the <sd-pretag id="sdPretag14540209623730" type="molecule" role="component" category="null">EC</sd-pretag> and the PRRs.</p><p>The <sd-pretag id="sdPretag14540209270280" type="molecule" role="component" category="null">EC</sd-pretag> can repress <sd-pretag id="sdPretag14719624658280" parent-tag-id="150">FT</sd-pretag> expression through at least three partially redundant pathways, involving coordinated control of <sd-pretag id="sdPretag14719622219990" parent-tag-id="142">CDF1</sd-pretag>, FKF1 and <sd-pretag id="sdPretag14541884685670" parent-tag-id="117">GI</sd-pretag> levels.</p><p>Similarly, the PRRs can activate <sd-pretag id="sdPretag14719624694530" parent-tag-id="150">FT</sd-pretag> expression through at least three pathways. Rectangles denote <sd-pretag id="sdPretag14540209660570" type="molecule" role="normalizing" category="null">protein</sd-pretag> species, and parallelograms denote transcript species. Solid and dashed lines indicate direct and indirect forms of regulation, respectively.</p> <graphic href="https://api.sourcedata.io/file.php?panel_id=20389"/></sd-panel></fig></article>